      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">OFFICES OF — ¶ N.Z. GEOLOGICAL SURVEY. ¶ NEW ZEALAND INSTITUTE. ¶ METEOROLOGICAL DEPART. ¶ Colonial Museum of New Zealand,...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">80.05.00e</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From John Buchanan</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M111, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Cyathea cunninghamii</seg> (MEL 224426) collected in the Dandenong Ranges, Vic, in October 1879. The item is dated to May 1880 on the presumption that M's inquiry to which Buchanan refers was prompted by information he had received about <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Cyathea%20medullaris">Cyathea medullaris</name>
                     </seg> in G. Marriner to M, 28 April 1880 (in this edition as 80-04-28a), and on the basis of Buchanan's reference to the 'recent discovery of <name key="Deyeuxia%20scabra%20">Deyeuxia scabra </name>in New Zealand'. In a paper that Buchanan read to the Wellington Institute on 21 February 1880 (Buchanan (1880a)), he included this species in a list of species recently added to the flora of NZ, with a reference to Plate 26 in his <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Indigenous grasses</seg> (Buchanan (1880)); but on that plate, the item was labelled as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Agrostis">Agrostis</name> quadriseta</seg>.</p>
               </note>
               <seg rend="form%20text"
                    style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, 'Times New Roman'; ">OFFICES OF —</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text"
                    style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, 'Times New Roman'; ">N.Z. GEOLOGICAL SURVEY.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text"
                    style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, 'Times New Roman'; ">NEW ZEALAND INSTITUTE.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text"
                    style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, 'Times New Roman'; ">METEOROLOGICAL DEPART.</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: center; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text"
                    style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, 'Times New Roman'; ">Colonial Museum of New Zealand,</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text"
                    style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, 'Times New Roman'; ">Wellington, <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>187<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron F. Von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Sir.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am glad that you have asked me the question concerning <name key="Cyathea%20medullaris">Cyathea medullaris</name>. There exists two distinct varieties of this species, first pointed out to me by the Maories north of Auckland, who have distinguishing names for both:</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="frame"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No 1. "Mamaku" in this variety the stipes form a distinct crown <note type="frame"/>where they join the stem as shewn in the sketch.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">80-05-00e_image01.jpg</seg>
                     <seg style="">.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In No 2. "Korau" the stipes grow straight from the stem which is generally more slender than in Mamaku.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">80-05-00e_image02.jpg.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Both varieties are abundant near Wellington although they are not distinguished by name, "Mamaku" being the only Maori name for <name key="Cyathea%20medullaris">Cyathea medullaris</name> here</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It may perhaps be worthy of notice whether differences exist in the fronds or other parts of the two varieties, for although I have often called the attention of others to this variety, I have always neglected to examine for myself.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am sorry I was not in possession of the Australian Flora<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Grasses were dealt with in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, pp. 449-670; the volume was published in <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>March 1878 (TL2).</p>
               </note> when this work on the New Zealand grasses was commenced,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Buchanan (1880).</p>
               </note> as the nomenclature might have by its aid been greatly improved. as one instance, the recent discovery of <name key="Deyeuxia%20scabra%20">Deyeuxia scabra </name>in New Zealand has made confusion of <name key="Agrostis">Agrostis</name>, several species of which should have been placed in Deyeuxia. however, as the work is chiefly for the use of New Zealand Squatters, any names will do for the purpose of distinction, and again in a benevolent point of view, it will give Kirk a wider scope to distinguish himself in pointing out its shortcomings, which he intends doing.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Remains Yours respectfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>John Buchanan<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">John Buchanan (1819-1898).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Agrostis">Agrostis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Cyathea%20medullaris">Cyathea medullaris</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Deyeuxia%20scabra%20">Deyeuxia scabra </name>
            </p>
         </div>
